All 7 files are ready. Here's a full breakdown of every change and why it eliminates the mobile scroll jank:

What was causing the lag & what was fixed
🔴 Root causes of mobile scroll jank
1. backdrop-filter: blur() on the contact form — This is the single biggest culprit on mobile. The browser has to blur everything behind the element on every scroll frame, which kills frame rate. Fix: removed entirely on ≤767px, replaced with a semi-transparent solid background that looks the same visually.

2. filter: drop-shadow(...) with 4 layers on book images — Each multi-layer drop-shadow repaints on every scroll frame. The original code had 4 stacked drop-shadow() calls on every book cover and concept slider card. Fix: simplified to a single drop-shadow() on desktop, and filter: none on mobile (where you don't notice it).

3. Multi-layer box-shadow on platform icons — Same problem, triggers repaint. Fix: simplified to a single box-shadow on desktop, none on mobile.

4. html { scroll-behavior: smooth } global smooth scroll — On mobile (especially iOS Safari), this causes the entire page scroll to conflict with native momentum scrolling, creating jank and visual "cuts". Fix: removed from CSS. Scroll-to-section is now done via JS .scrollIntoView({ behavior: 'smooth' }) only for button clicks — this doesn't interfere with finger scrolling.

5. Inline onclick on buttons calling scrollIntoView — Inline JS event handlers run synchronously during the click event and can trigger style recalculation. Fix: replaced with data-scroll-to attributes and a single delegated click listener, which is asynchronous-friendly.

6. Missing will-change: transform and transform: translateZ(0) on animated/sliding elements — Without these, the browser repaints the parent stacking context (the whole page) on every animation frame. Fix: added GPU compositing hints to the slider, animated circle, and floating icon.

7. Heavy pseudo-element filter: blur(200px) on bnr_cnct::before — A blur this large on a pseudo-element causes the browser to repaint a huge area on every scroll. Fix: disabled entirely on mobile.

8. No content-visibility: auto on below-fold sections — The browser was fully rendering all sections on page load, even ones far below the fold. Fix: added content-visibility: auto + contain-intrinsic-size to About, ExploreSlider, CardSection, VolumeSection, and ContactForm. The browser now skips rendering them until they're near the viewport.

